#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/black_as_a_server.md:1
msgid "Black as a server (blackd)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/black_as_a_server.md:3
msgid ""
"`blackd` is a small HTTP server that exposes _Black_'s functionality over a "
"simple protocol. The main benefit of using it is to avoid the cost of "
"starting up a new _Black_ process every time you want to blacken a file."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/black_as_a_server.md:8
msgid ""
"`blackd` should not be run as a publicly accessible server as there are no "
"security precautions in place to prevent abuse. **It is intended for local "
"use only**."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/black_as_a_server.md:12
msgid "Usage"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/black_as_a_server.md:14
msgid ""
"`blackd` is not packaged alongside _Black_ by default because it has "
"additional dependencies. You will need to execute `pip install 'black[d]'` "
"to install it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/black_as_a_server.md:17
msgid ""
"You can start the server on the default port, binding only to the local "
"interface by running `blackd`. You will see a single line mentioning the "
"server's version, and the host and port it's listening on. `blackd` will "
"then print an access log similar to most web servers on standard output, "
"merged with any exception traces caused by invalid formatting requests."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/black_as_a_server.md:23
msgid ""
"`blackd` provides even less options than _Black_. You can see them by "
"running `blackd --help`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/black_as_a_server.md:30
msgid "You can test that blackd is working using `curl`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/black_as_a_server.md:32
msgid ""
"blackd --bind-port 9090 &  # or let blackd choose a port\n"
"curl -s -XPOST \"localhost:9090\" -d \"print('valid')\"\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/black_as_a_server.md:37
msgid "Or using the python client:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/black_as_a_server.md:39
msgid ""
"import asyncio\n"
"\n"
"from blackd.client import BlackDClient\n"
"\n"
"async def main():\n"
"    client = BlackDClient(url=\"http://127.0.0.1:9090\")\n"
"    unformatted_code = \"def hello(): print('Hello, World!')\"\n"
"    formatted_code = await client.format_code(unformatted_code)\n"
"    print(formatted_code)\n"
"\n"
"if __name__ == \"__main__\":\n"
"    asyncio.run(main())\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/black_as_a_server.md:54
msgid ""
"Cross-origin browser requests are rejected by default. If you need to access "
"`blackd` from a browser-based client, pass one or more `--cors-allow-origin` "
"options to allow specific origins."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/black_as_a_server.md:58
msgid "Protocol"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/black_as_a_server.md:60
msgid ""
"`blackd` only accepts `POST` requests at the `/` path. The body of the "
"request should contain the python source code to be formatted, encoded "
"according to the `charset` field in the `Content-Type` request header. If no "
"`charset` is specified, `blackd` assumes `UTF-8`. Request bodies are limited "
"to 5 MiB by default; use `--max-body-size` to change that limit."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/black_as_a_server.md:66
msgid ""
"There are a few HTTP headers that control how the source code is formatted. "
"These correspond to command line flags for _Black_. There is one exception "
"to this: `X-Protocol-Version` which if present, should have the value `1`, "
"otherwise the request is rejected with `HTTP 501` (Not Implemented)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/black_as_a_server.md:71
msgid "The headers controlling how source code is formatted are:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/black_as_a_server.md:73
msgid "`X-Line-Length`: corresponds to the `--line-length` command line flag."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/black_as_a_server.md:74
msgid ""
"`X-Skip-Source-First-Line`: corresponds to the `--skip-source-first-line` "
"command line flag. If present and its value is not an empty string, the "
"first line of the source code will be ignored."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/black_as_a_server.md:77
msgid ""
"`X-Skip-String-Normalization`: corresponds to the `--skip-string-"
"normalization` command line flag. If present and its value is not the empty "
"string, no string normalization will be performed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/black_as_a_server.md:80
msgid ""
"`X-Skip-Magic-Trailing-Comma`: corresponds to the `--skip-magic-trailing-"
"comma` command line flag. If present and its value is not an empty string, "
"trailing commas will not be used as a reason to split lines."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/black_as_a_server.md:83
msgid ""
"`X-Preview`: corresponds to the `--preview` command line flag. If present "
"and its value is not an empty string, experimental and potentially "
"disruptive style changes will be used."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/black_as_a_server.md:86
msgid ""
"`X-Unstable`: corresponds to the `--unstable` command line flag. If present "
"and its value is not an empty string, experimental style changes that are "
"known to be buggy will be used."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/black_as_a_server.md:89
msgid ""
"`X-Enable-Unstable-Feature`: corresponds to the `--enable-unstable-feature` "
"flag. The contents of the flag must be a comma-separated list of unstable "
"features to be enabled. Example: `X-Enable-Unstable-Feature: feature1, "
"feature2`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/black_as_a_server.md:92
msgid ""
"`X-Fast-Or-Safe`: if set to `fast`, `blackd` will act as _Black_ does when "
"passed the `--fast` command line flag."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/black_as_a_server.md:94
msgid ""
"`X-Python-Variant`: if set to `pyi`, `blackd` will act as _Black_ does when "
"passed the `--pyi` command line flag. Otherwise, its value must correspond "
"to a Python version or a set of comma-separated Python versions, optionally "
"prefixed with `py`. For example, to request code that is compatible with "
"Python 3.5 and 3.6, set the header to `py3.5,py3.6`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/black_as_a_server.md:99
msgid ""
"`X-Diff`: corresponds to the `--diff` command line flag. If present, a diff "
"of the formats will be output."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/black_as_a_server.md:102
msgid ""
"If any of these headers are set to invalid values, `blackd` returns a `HTTP "
"400` error response, mentioning the name of the problematic header in the "
"message body."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/black_as_a_server.md:105
msgid ""
"Apart from the above, `blackd` can produce the following response codes:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/black_as_a_server.md:107
msgid ""
"`HTTP 204`: If the input is already well-formatted. The response body is "
"empty."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/black_as_a_server.md:108
msgid ""
"`HTTP 200`: If formatting was needed on the input. The response body "
"contains the blackened Python code, and the `Content-Type` header is set "
"accordingly."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/black_as_a_server.md:110
msgid ""
"`HTTP 400`: If the input contains a syntax error. Details of the error are "
"returned in the response body."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/black_as_a_server.md:112
msgid ""
"`HTTP 500`: If there was any other kind of error while trying to format the "
"input. The response body contains a textual representation of the error."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/black_as_a_server.md:115
msgid ""
"The response headers include a `X-Black-Version` header containing the "
"version of _Black_."
msgstr ""
